g.text: K-Means is a centroid based algorithm whose goal is split the dataset into k clusters in which
every element belongs to the clustering with its closest centroid (mean element)
Randomly select K points as centroids
Repeat until the centroids don't change
Form K clusters by assigning all the points
Since they are randomly chosen, different runs
- First run with an high number
Most of the time there isn't a "right" number of clusters (k).
Therefore we use the knee (or elbow) approach
set all data as one big cluster
repeat until the list of clusters contain K clusters
add the clusters from the bisection with lowest error
K-means suffers with clusters having different sizes or densities
It only identifies spherical shaped clusters
But also.. it suffers in presence of outliers
- it produces clusters of similar size
